{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14097"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14097"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.08,0.02,0.2,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101531"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6765"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4999"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101531"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to a nephrologist for routine follow-up of chronic kidney disease. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include metformin, glibenclamide, perindopril, hydrochlorothiazide, and lercanidipine. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR): 47 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin-to-creatinine ratio: 3 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["G3a A1","G3b A3","G4 A2","G3b A1","G3a A3"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease (CKD) stage is best described as \u003Cstrong\u003EG3a A1\u003C/strong\u003E. The staging of CKD is based on two factors: the estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) and the albuminuria grade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe eGFR of 47 mL/min/1.73m2 falls into the range of 45-59 mL/min/1.73m2, which corresponds to stage G3a. The \u0027G\u0027 in the staging refers to GFR category. The stages of CKD based on eGFR are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG1: \u226590 mL/min/1.73m2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG2: 60-89 mL/min/1.73m2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EG3a\u003C/strong\u003E: 45-59 mL/min/1.73m2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG3b: 30-44 mL/min/1.73m2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG4: 15-29 mL/min/1.73m2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG5: \u0026lt;15 mL/min/1.73m2 (or commenced dialysis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe albuminuria grade is determined by the urinary albumin excretion. In this case, the ACR is 3 mg/mmol, which falls into the A1 category. Based on the urinary albumin-creatinine ratio, the categories for albuminuria are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA1\u003C/strong\u003E (normal): \u0026lt;2.5 mg/mmol (male) and \u0026lt;3.5 mg/mmol (female)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA2 (moderately increased albuminuria): 2.5\u201325 mg/mmol (male) and 3.5\u201335 mg/mmol (female)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA3 (severely increased albuminuria): \u0026gt;25 mg/mmol (male) and \u0026gt;35 mg/mmol (female).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote the terms \u0027moderately increased albuminuria\u0027 and \u0027severely increased albuminuria\u0027 are preferable to the terms \u0027microalbuminuria\u0027 and \u0027macroalbuminuria\u0027 respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccurately classifying chronic kidney disease is essential to provide accurate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is staged based on eGFR and albuminuria grade.","The terms \u0027moderately increased albuminuria\u0027 and \u0027severely increased albuminuria\u0027 are preferable to the terms \u0027microalbuminuria\u0027 and \u0027macroalbuminuria\u0027 respectively for chronic kidney disease staging.","Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD)  staging helps guide management decisions and determine prognosis."],"references":["RACGP - Chapter 13: Chronic kidney disease prevention and management [Internet]. Racgp.org.au. 2018. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/national-guide/chapter-13-chronic-kidney-disease-prevention-and-m"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14097"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data"